The food is great. The pizza is very solid, excellent crust, cheese that achieves that ideal even melt, tangy sauce. The sides are just as good if not better - while in most small pie shops like this one the sides will be kind of an afterthought, here they're fantastic.  The service really makes this place stand out, especially if you're a regular. The staff remembers you, smiles, and have frequently added small bonuses, like an extra garlic knot or mozzarella stick, to my orders. I highly recommend this pizzeria both to locals who want a regular spot, and to visitors who want a taste of that legendary old fashioned small business New York pizza shop experience, which is rarer and rarer nowadays.

How the mighty have fallen. What had once been one of New York City's most elegant and beautiful restaurants, with amazing food, is not even a shadow of its former self. Yes, the decor is still handsome, but nowhere near what it was in its heyday. More a well-appointed mausoleum than anything else. The service was all right, but the food quite awful. The smoked salmon was dry and flavorless, the lamb only adequate, and the Beef Stroganoff (which, whatever it was, wasn't Beef Stroganoff) this side of inedible. Adding insult to that inedibility were the prices. Outrageously expensive. The Russian Tea Room completely lost its way a good quarter of a century ago and has long lost any reason for being. I'm awarding two stars only for old time's sake. Very sad. And very bad.

I'm new-ish to the neighborhood, so I've only been going to George's for about a year, but it's the only pizza place I go to here!  My roommates and I got it the day we moved in, and continue to order it.  It's delicious, the sauce is tasty, the crust is a thicker than usual NY crust (but you can order thin if you prefer) and it's always delivered hot.  The owner and one of the other guys (who delivers) are so nice, always friendly.  When you go in and order a slice, they give you a garlic knot with it. They've been rated as part of the top pizza places on a few lists and reviews, and I agree with them.

Washington Heights does not provide a lot of options when it comes to take out, and often, you find yourself settling  for food that's just ok. But if you live within George's delivery area, you won't have to settle where pizza is concerned. This is solid NY pizza, tasty and reliable. George's has been an institution here for years, and has made some top pizza lists -- I think it was Timeout NY that included it in its top 100 pizza places in NYC. Try ordering your pie thin crust.

On the strength of the rave reviews (4 stars with 26 reviews), our family began ordering pizzas here last year after a couple years of being disappointed with others in the neighborhood, but now, after six or seven times having pizzas delivered (mostly plain, but once or twice with a topping or two), we're calling it a failed experiment.  The sauce is straight from a can, the crust too thick and chewy and the cheese not browned. Oddly, when stopping in off the street, an individual slice, if reheated not fresh, comes with the cheese a little more browned and the crust a little crispier, which is much better.
